rmk:
Although the bird was watched by many observers, the bird was extremely
secretive and only a few good photographs were available.
The ID is considered to be almost certain based on the available photographs and
sighting reports (ID still being discussed).
The sound spectrum is also compatible with the call in XC21210.
If the ID is confirmed, this is probably the second record of
this species in Osaka Castle Park according to the regular observer(s).
Although entire Japan is shown as "breeding" range
on BirdLife International and NatureServe (2011),
the species is basically "passage" in Osaka and nearby
prefectures.  Only few instances of breeding in this region
have been reported, and were usually more than ten years ago.
There have been occasionally records of singing individuals
in the coastal region of Osaka Prefecture in the breeding season,
and some may be breeding, but the status has not been confirmed recently.
The only well-known regular breeding site in the nearby region
was in Nara Prefecture, but this population stopped
breeding about ten years ago.
(source: http://voiceofnara.jp/news221.html).
The last breeding record in Kyoto Prefecture dates back
to the 1980s.
Human chanting and some other noise in the background.
